Title: E System Intensity Explanation
WorkoutDescription: E System Intensity Explanation E1 Easy pace is mainly used for warming-up, for some respite between steady intervals, or as a workout on its own for recovery between hard training days. The pace is very comfortable and hardly causes a sweat. Sensation of effort is generally low. Continuous conversation is possible. E2A Often referred to as Extensive Endurance, the intention here is to train at or surrounding your aerobic threshold (AeT) and develop efficiency and endurance. The Steady zone is defined by a feeling of controlled, calm efficiency, and conditions the body to burn more fat and increase the amount of work that can be accomplished (economy!) while remaining comfortable, aerobic and fat burning. Held for extensive periods (eg. 4-6 hours of cycling) steady becomes harder more from muscle glycogen depletion than from the intensity level. If you are dialed in correctly then you should be able to back up the effort physically and mentally day-in, day-out. Be sure to not let steady turn into a Mod-Hard/Tempo effort, or you will be training too intensively to develop the targeted energy system. For running, a relaxed (NOT with a heavy exhalation, but relaxed!) 4-3 (4 steps for breathing in, 3 steps for breathing out) is typical of steady. This is the pace where you train your oxygen processing mechanisms, relevant for health and fitness as well as performance. Steady training forms the bulk of the training program. Steady is one gear up from easy and is a pace where you can still have a conversation but it is not an easy/recovery pace. E2B Intensive Endurance. Maintaining this pace requires a higher level of concentration. It is An upper aerobic effort (ie) you are still at aerobic rates but as fast as you go within that range. For most, this is Ironman swim, bike and run intensity.breathing becomes deeper but is still controlled free of oxygen debt, but not as much as at E3. Its a strong, controlled effort, but not hammering. It is still comfortable, but you know you are working. Its about the IMP TT/race pace for bike and run individual time trials. E2B is a comfortably solid pace. E3 Often labeled Tempo, leg fatigue gets more pronounced at this level. Continuous conversation is getting harder- It equates well with a half ironman pace effort for bike and run, for swimming the 30-minute time trial effort should approximate the E3. You are literally just under threshold zones  to go any harder will force a move into threshold. This is effort is also used for efficiency  (ie) good speed without losing form. AT Often labeled Threshold training, leg fatigue gets more pronounced at this level. Continuous conversation is difficult due to the depth/frequency of breathing. The effort level is sufficiently high that it is mentally very taxing. The fitter you are the longer you can maintain this level for. It equates well with a 1-hour race/time trial effort for bike and run, for swimming the 1500mtr- time trial effort should approximate the AT. To go any harder will force a slowing down due to oxygen deficit and an over-acidification of the muscles. Very important is to balance your effort precariously at this point and not go too hard, or else you risk not being able to get through the training set. For fit athletes, a 35-40km cycling time trial is a good representation of AT, as is a 15-17K running race. A 30K bike and a 10K run are typically performed just a bit faster than the AT. Olympic distance triathlon (non-drafting) is typically performed at AT by fit athletes. Very Hard AT+ This is VO2 Max training, at intensities of 90-100% of VO2 Max. Conversation is not possible at this effort due to "ragged" breathing..you dont want to be answering questions at this intensity! Its the 6-30 minute time trial pace/effort. For elite runners, this means 3-10k race pace/effort. This training increases oxygen uptake and AEROBIC CAPACITY. The pace feels hard initially, then uncomfortable within just a few minutes. There is a noticeable increase in ventilation and lactic acid build-up (burning) in the muscles.

Title: Program Notes
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Focus on speed and tolerance. Tolerance means exactly what it says, so you are teaching yourself to tolerate what feels uncomfortable and the only way to do that is to allow the discomfort and regulate yourself within it. Its not a measure of how fast you go at all, it's a measure of what you can tolerate and how long you can sustain it for. Speed in endurance sport is a by product of that, focus on speed all you like, but if you can't sustain it, its over before it starts. Strength, speed, power and flow all stems for your ability to down regulate while in discomfort, that means you have to teach yourself how to embody it and stay out of resistance. If you create a story of the pain, because are focused on a mind in pain, you will feel more pain in your body. So, stay with the pain in your body and leave it there, don't go up into your head with it. Have a great week Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Fear # 1
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.
CoachComments: o False Evidence Appearing Real. o Fear lives in only two places=Past and future, it cannot live in the present. o Life provides the necessary responses for survival; the multiplication of mind is not needed. o Dont let the emotion rise into the mind and become a fear story. Break the fear circuit by feeling it.

Title: AT Pace / cadence bigger gear / E2B Recovery
WorkoutDescription: Warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 3mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling.. . Set 1 6x 3mins big gear as Olympic Distance watts 85rpm, absolute threshold power. on 4mins E2B in between . Complete rest of ride @ low aerobic levels E1-E2A low
CoachComments: Focus around staying on top of a bigger gear at high power, try not to move -lock it in and stay smooth through that 3mins (i.e.) let the pain come through focus pedal technique not by actually trying to smash yourself. a lot of the time efforting to go real hard=crappy results, focused power is a much better focus.
AthleteComments: *17/06/2025 Aaron Kiss: My current power meter reads around 8-10% lower than my lab power test so I just adjust the values accordingly. Held around 285-290w for the 3mins & 235-240w for the 4mins*

Title: Track 1000's
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 5x 1000 mid AT on 400 walk/float recovery. . Warm down- 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: If this session cannot be done as track then do it as fartlek as- Warm up- 7mins E1 7mins E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 5x 3:30mins mid AT on 2:30 walk/float recovery. . Warm down - 7mins easy float. ...................... Run the 1000 or 3:30mins on the low to mid threshold range. Don't blow your candles out by going overspeed. This is about the function of the whole session so we are looking for flow and function. Float the recovery by walking 200, then jog the next 200 keeping the heart rate at about 75-80% so its not totally off on the 200 float. We want your heart rate to come off but not totally off. Be careful not to overdo the first 500, let it build.
AthleteComments: *17/06/2025 Aaron Kiss: Very controlled, all reps in the low 3:30s*

Title: Speed Endurance
WorkoutDescription: Warm up- 8x 50 first drill on 50 building Set 1- speed 3000 10x 100 fast but soft leaving on 30 rest 800 pull sub E1 5x 100 fast but soft leave 30 rest 300 pull sub E1 8x 50 fast on 60seconds rest . set 2 10x 100 30 rest very easy pull paddles . Warmdown Easy 200 mix.
CoachComments: These speed sets are set to fast, but relax as much as you can. Sounds like a paradox but it isn't, focus on your relaxation at speed.
AthleteComments: *18/06/2025 Aaron Kiss: 100s off 1:45 coming in smoothly 1:11/12. 50s off 1:00 in around 0:33-0:34. First bit of faster swimming since the last race so a lot of progression from this. More pull than im used to but feels good!*

Title: Low hrate run - Strides
WorkoutDescription: A 90min dead flat run. Run at the lowest possible oxygen cost for the best form. Incorporate 5x 60seconds building to high turnover on the 3min cycle.
CoachComments: This run is about fat burning low aerobic run form. Don't run so slow that the form is hampered but run where you are most comfortable on a cross benefit of form and function

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Flow
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.
CoachComments: o Wherever and whatever you put your focus on will expand. o Where focus goes, energy flows. o If your focus is negative or fear based, that energy will expand the fear and negativity. o When focus is process based you are routing yourself in now. In reality. o Felt sense focus creates flow. It simplifies things down to process and self.

Title: E2B-Threshold builds / Equal Recovery -Builder
WorkoutDescription: Warmup pyramid as- o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 3mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling . Build Set - {3x 8mins on 8mins recovery} as- 2mins @ E2A high 2mins @ E2B 2mins @ E3 2mins @ AT . Warm down- 10mins very easy gears.
CoachComments: This is a simple build from high E2A to AT plus or minus 5. The recovery is 8mins at E2B and 70-75rpm, the focus is to have peaks that come back to E2B, not easy. Cadences are marked in builder. The focus here is to learn how to recover and move and back from E2B without coming all the way off.

Title: Fartlek Broken Swim

CoachComments: Essentially this is five times 6x 100 broken but at fartlek speeds, the higher intensity efforts are low rest and the aerobic efforts are longer rest to give you the space to able to complete the higher intensity efforts with good form.

Title: Aerobic Form Climbs Road
WorkoutDescription: Aerobic endurance on climbs. Keep all climbs seated and E2B or level. Keep the flats light around E1-E2A.
CoachComments: Use gravity here, ride the climbs slow, pedalling smoothly and keeping your upper body relaxed. As the inertia is low the strength benefit is maximised giving you a good workout of strength benefit for low aerobic cost. Leave the ego on the shelf and check your form, are you unnecessarily moving the body to add to momentum? Isolate the working muscles and remind yourself to breathe and relax into it.

Title: Track 200's
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 12x 200 @ 105-110% of threshold on 200 walk back recovery. . Warm down- 1200 E2A 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: TRACK VERSION: This session overspeed. But focus on turnover here. Start the effort building leg speed. Start the rep with feet shoulder width apart and lean from the ankles until you feel your toes claw the ground, this is correct lean angle, fall forward from that stance and let the leg speed come. Flow, relax and let it happen, by the end of the rep you want to be fast. The recovery is walk/jog, as slowly as you need to refract to the next rep. You can also do these as jog/walk back to start.

Title: Out and Back Tempo
WorkoutDescription: Warm up  Run 35mins to turnaround E1 building to E2B low over back 5mins Set- run back from turnaround @ 30mins tempo or 70.3 pace. If it hovers around top of mid E2B to E3 thats ok, but don't move towards AT Warmdown as-  25mins E1
CoachComments: This is an out and back run. On the way back we want a tempo pace so the higest pace you can hold with a degree of relaxation still in place. Looking for a long sustained effort that doesn't ebb form nor speed.

Title: Pace shifts AT four hundreds
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 300 easy 6x 50 building on 50, Main Set-(3x pull, 3xPull and paddles) 8x 400 on 5:30 - alternate- 30 strokes with force E3-AT but no tension 30 strokes relaxed E1 . Warm down- 300 pull 8x 50 on 55.
CoachComments: The main set is fartlek. Alternating force with easy relaxed swimming. When you move up from the relaxed pace try to apply force without tensing or creating mental tension. A good idea is to consciously try to relax as you apply the force. Often the tension is a physical reaction to a mental stimulus.

Title: Program Notes
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Full of key sessions built around tangible development but apply liberal amounts of attention to recovery and fuelling. Caretake each moment when you are in efforts. Respond to the challenge and quit any evasions that your mind comes with. Fully inhabit the situation you are in, allow it, invite it, go deeper into it. If the numbers aren't lining up, stay where you are, make no decisions. Be discerning enough in the moment to understand that any decision you make to move away from what is happening is going to follow you into your racing. You can only race the way you have practised, thats why the awareness and the presence in training are so important. If you are in resistance in training, you'll be in resistance in races. All you have to do is find the ways you resist and then apply liberal amounts of acceptance. Fuel well this week, stay on top of sleep and keep in mind that recovery primary. Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Non Resistance #3
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o All roads lead inwards, every outside hook is resistance dressed in sheep's clothing. When you catch yourself in outer resistance, go within and let it be the way it is. o All your challenges and discomforts are your opportunity's cloaked in the minds resistance, no one gets anywhere by attaching to feeling good and comfortable. Life teaches us most when we are stretched and out of our comfort zones. o The past is resistance, the future is resistance, don't look for safety in them, none exists. The only security you have is in this very moment, because that is all the reality we have. o Motivation is intrinsic, regardless of what you think motivates you, its coming from within, not without. If you think something motivates you, its not true, it simply uncovers your deeper truth, you already are motivation, it arises from within you. Thoughts and belief that is outside you is again, resistance.

Title: Program Notes
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Built around aerobic but open to discussion on Monday. Bit of an overload week, chasing some adaptation here. You are going to need to fuel well and sleep well. If you don't or can't, adjust downwards with intensity. Keep it real: When you think about developing speed, generally you are thinking of working to develop sustainable, functional speed. You cannot drag your body kicking and screaming into form by training at speeds which you cannot possibly sustain due to a lack of strength or endurance. Functionality is partly about being realistic. If you can learn to relax into speed, then it stands to reason that your capacity to sustain it will vastly improve too. We have this idea that speed equates to tension and effort, however this is not true - effort counts, yet effort is negated by tension. Practise relaxing into your speed reps, let the flow come, let the muscles in your face relax and that same energy which was previously being wasted will then be channelled back into your performance levels. If you can touch the threshold zone without ruining yourself in the process, you are developing and evolving. Your speed will also evolve and develop sustainability - theres that s word again. Always zoom out and think about the long-term. If you need to change any of this, sing out. Have a great week, Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - It is what it is #2
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o Don't bullshit yourself that a successful training session or race is anything other than a present moment. That's all there is to it. o Authenticity is the road to truth in an athletic process, people run out of steam because they create mental pictures that are impossible to live up to, why? Because it feels safer, it's rubbish, there is no safety. Get real and get after it. o Life is what you make of it, if you make it about drama, it will be drama, if you make it about fear it will be fear, if you make it about presence, your essential being will be present, nothing is more powerful than that. o Give up your ghosts, face the shadow that says you can't, take away the T an you have can, that's how close you really are.

Title: Program Notes
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Lets use this as the jump off point. We can work it in and out of group sessions as need be. This is a pretty strong week and it will test you so fuel well and sleep well. More of a week structured around quality and it all has a purpose, zero junk. Just watch the stories you tell yourself about pain here this week. Much of our thinking around pain is extremely limited. The idea that it shouldnt be here and that its something to avoid makes it near impossible to turn the screws on your competitors because you keep moving away from it in your head. I cant take this, I cant keep this up. Because we spend so much of our time counting down the time left on efforts, we are unconsciously counting down the pain in races and assessing if you can take much more. That is not presence in the body, its an exhaustive mental battle that you cant think your way out of. Take it into the body, trust its intelligence, be there for your own pain, dont abandon it, dont abandon yourself. Now you are sending a message to your nervous system that you are not going to hide under the bed again and that pain is safe to be felt. If you dont train this, the mind starts looking for exits, escape routes and outs. It will use any bullshit to disengage. How many races have you gone home with your tail between your legs and pissed off because in your heart you knew you believed your thoughts? Take it into the body, watch it, feel it, allow it. Stay present. Have a great week, Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Track 200's
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 12x 200 @ 105-110% of threshold on 200 walk back recovery. . Warm down- 1200 E2A 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: TRACK VERSION: This session overspeed. But focus on turnover here. Start the effort building leg speed. Start the rep with feet shoulder width apart and lean from the ankles until you feel your toes claw the ground, this is correct lean angle, fall forward from that stance and let the leg speed come. Flow, relax and let it happen, by the end of the rep you want to be fast. The recovery is walk/jog, as slowly as you need to refract to the next rep. You can also do these as jog/walk back to start.

Title: Program Notes -TENTATIVE
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, I've spread the leg load and made it specific using swimming as the wedge so we get the best of each session. Don't look at the Sat session as a non key session, it is very key. Keep it low intensity but don't stop pedalling, no coasting, just keep hitting the pedals but stay relaxed and low h/rate. Everything here has purpose, try to remind yourself pre session to come to the specific focus, its really easy to get tired and bored and just go through the motions. The actual discipline in this caper is to stay engaged when its boring, and lets face it, sometimes its a grind. Its your level of intension, attention and focus even when its boring that really makes the difference. Stay curious, Gilesy.

Title: AT Threshold / E2B Low Recovery - Builder
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 10mins E1 5mins build E2B low . Main Set - 4x 5mins / 5mins recovery, See pre-activity notes on this one. . Warm down 5mins E2B low 5mins jog 5mins walk

The idea is to learn how to recover and relax in the mid aerobic range after an effort. This promotes better general conditioning and better lactate buffering.

Title: Program Notes
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Punchy, but don't get punched. Just fuel well, sleep well, pace well. Think long range, not short range, building form not forcing it. There's enough here to keepm progression moving as long as you are aware enough to know when you need to pull back on the throttle a little. just a small word on stress, if you have a high stress day. don't match it with a high stress session, pull back on it and just go aerobic if you have a stressful one. A stressful day is not a signal to smash yourself, although I understand that is often the thing you want to do. Just ease into it and see how it feels. Also just keep in mind that thing is running in arrears, what you do today has broader impacts later, like the end of next week even, so once again just to be aware what you do today doesn't necessarily show up tomorrow. Have a great week, Gilesy.

Title: Program Notes:
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, This week has a speed strength focus and an underpinning aerobic function function. To be clear aerobic threshold sits at around 85-88% of anaerobic threshold. This intensity is highly trainable, doesn't wreck your legs. If you develop good speed here your general speed will explode. I saw it again and again when the group were together, their success rested on the development of that specific intensity. It works across the board, and it takes patience and control to harness it. It also takes a careful management of ego, because if it is left undeveloped its pretty slow. If however you get efficient, strong and fast at that intensity it directly is reflected in race specific outcomes, backend improves out of sight. Have a great week, Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Association #3

Title: Power Intervals -SE

CoachComments: Power Intervals Hard intervals on big gear at 60-70rpm. In that minute you are leaning on it hard but not a sprint. Maintain the form. This is an effective strength and power builder so just be mindful you are better off having the highest power towards the end of the rep rather than at the start of it. Title: Beach Starts -Open Water 1500/Swim Run Shuttle

Title: Aerobic Form Climbs Road
WorkoutDescription: Aerobic endurance on climbs. Keep all climbs seated and E2B or level. Keep the flats light around E1-E2A.
CoachComments: Use gravity here, ride the climbs slow, pedalling smoothly and keeping your upper body relaxed. As the inertia is low the strength benefit is maximised giving you a good workout of strength benefit for low aerobic cost. Leave the ego on the shelf and check your form, are you unnecessarily moving the body to add to momentum? Isolate the working muscles and remind yourself to breathe and relax into it.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Flow #2- Reminders

Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.
CoachComments: o No flow, no go. Disjointed performances are a by-product of a lack of flow. In flow- it goes fast, out of flow its like pulling teeth. o Use mental cues to gently bring yourself back to flow and process. o Pour the focus of the performance through the self, always through the self. This is your definition of self-trust. o The powered focus of desire, gut and heart, it comes from the center, not the mind.

Title: Track 1500's or Fartlek
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 5x 1500 low to mid AT on 400 walk/float recovery. . Warm down- 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: If this session cannot be done as track then do it as fartlek as- Warm up- 7mins E1 7mins E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 5x 5:30mins mid AT on 2:30 walk/float recovery. . Warm down - 7mins easy float. ...................... Run the 1500 or 5:30mins on the low to mid threshold range. Don't blow your candles out by going overspeed. This is about the function of the whole session so we are looking for flow and function. Float the recovery by walking 200, then jog the next 200 keeping the heart rate at about 75-80% so its not totally off on the 200 float. We want your heart rate to come off but not totally off. Be careful not to overdo the first 500, let it build.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - It is what it is #3
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o If you have a bad race or a bad session, what good does it do to ruminate? If it is, it's trying to teach you something, what is it trying to teach you? Listen to what is and you will find out. o Avoidance is the acid that eats at our dreams, its caustic, apathy takes a ride on it and creates frustration and then we think we are frustrated when in fact we are just avoidant. o Talk is good for movies, if you don't mean it and it's not really true, just don't say it, to yourself or to others. Actions speak louder than words. Action from where you are at right now, is best anchor to progress. o Progress is the sum of its parts. All of its parts arise from this place of what is, if it looks good, use it. If it looks bad, use it. Maximise what you have to work with.

CoachComments: So these are done at tempo E3 so it's solid but it is sustainable. The goal of the session is to reach the final 400's with strongest form so starting conservative is important.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Reactivity #1
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.

Title: Low hrate run - Strides
WorkoutDescription: A 70min dead flat run. Run at the lowest possible oxygen cost for the best form. Incorporate 5x 60seconds building to high turnover on the 3min cycle.
CoachComments: This run is about fat burning low aerobic run form. Don't run so slow that the form is hampered but run where you are most comfortable on a cross benefit of form and function

Title: Pace shifts AT four hundreds
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 300 easy 6x 50 building on 50, Main Set-(3x pull, 3xPull and paddles) 8x 400 on 5:30 - alternate- 30 strokes with force E3-AT but no tension 30 strokes relaxed E1 . Warm down- 300 pull 8x 50 on 55.
CoachComments: The main set is fartlek. Alternating force with easy relaxed swimming. When you move up from the relaxed pace try to apply force without tensing or creating mental tension. A good idea is to consciously try to relax as you apply the force. Often the tension is a physical reaction to a mental stimulus.

Title: Program Notes-Asia champs two Weeks
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Full of key sessions built around tangible development but apply liberal amounts of attention to recovery and fuelling as we need to start pulling back here with 2 weeks to go. Caretake each moment when you are in efforts. Respond to the challenge and quit any evasions that your mind comes with. Fully inhabit the situation you are in, allow it, invite it, go deeper into it. If the numbers aren't lining up, stay where you are, make no decisions. Be discerning enough in the moment to understand that any decision you make to move away from what is happening is going to follow you into your racing. You can only race the way you have practised, thats why the awareness and the presence in training are so important. If you are in resistance in training, you'll be in resistance in races. All you have to do is find the ways you resist and then apply liberal amounts of acceptance. Fuel well this week, stay on top of sleep and keep in mind that recovery is primary. Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Alternating 200's

Title: Open Water
WorkoutDescription: 15mins warm up main set 5x 400 as fartlek 2x{ 100 out surge +race pace 100 back in E2B Beach recovery 2mins 15mins warm down
CoachComments: This session is about start practise. So from the beach try to chase a pace off the beach that is realistic to race start, really go for it then change the pace back to E2B and try to recovery while still at a decent clip. This is very trainable and a skill worth having in your back pocket.

Title: Spike Power (ITU)
WorkoutDescription: Warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling. . Main Set: - 15x 1min effort (at or slightly above threshold, ie. 120-130% FTP; RPE best effort you can hold for 1min.). Efforts performed at race cadence 80-85rpm, 90secs easy spin recovery between efforts. Repeat this sequence 20 times or until cooked.. . Cool Down: - 10min easy/aerobic.
CoachComments: These are on the red line. But let it come, try not to force it, start the first 20secs building into the power then let it fly but keep in mind theres 8 of them.

Title: Track 200's
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 12x 200 @ threshold on 200 walk back recovery. . Warm down- 1200 E2A 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: TRACK VERSION: This session overspeed. But focus on turnover here. Start the effort building leg speed. Start the rep with feet shoulder width apart and lean from the ankles until you feel your toes claw the ground, this is correct lean angle, fall forward from that stance and let the leg speed come. Flow, relax and let it happen, by the end of the rep you want to be fast. The recovery is walk/jog, as slowly as you need to refract to the next rep. You can also do these as jog/walk back to start. NON TRACK VERSION: If you can't get to track all you need a 200 meter stretch of road or field. Walk/jog back to start. If that is the case the warm up becomes 8mins E1, 8mins E2A. Warm down 8mins E2A, 5mins E1.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Non Resistance #3
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o All roads lead inwards, every outside hook is resistance dressed in sheep's clothing. When you catch yourself in outer resistance, go within and let it be the way it is. o All your challenges and discomforts are your opportunity's cloaked in the minds resistance, no one gets anywhere by attaching to feeling good and comfortable. Life teaches us most when we are stretched and out of our comfort zones. o The past is resistance, the future is resistance, don't look for safety in them, none exists. The only security you have is in this very moment, because that is all the reality we have. o Motivation is intrinsic, regardless of what you think motivates you, its coming from within, not without. If you think something motivates you, its not true, it simply uncovers your deeper truth, you already are motivation, it arises from within you. Thoughts and belief that is outside you is again, resistance.

Title: Notes-Race Week Asia Triathlon Championships Istanbul
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, I always like to keep tapers very similar, if not the same to eliminate any doubts. Keep it simple, do your grounding, stay with yourself. Breathe, relax the tension in the front of your body constantly and consistently. On race day, don't forget the "dog". Its inside out regardless of what is happening. The flight is in the dog, not in the fight. Keep this super simple and enough here to keep you moving. Do the vis, keep yourself calm, breathe into your balls often this week and prepare to go deep. Don't change anything. Don't go looking for more. Let the racing do the work. Avoid touching it up in training. Don't test, trust! Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Program Notes
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Lets take this week as just use it to keep moving and stay engaged but try to trelax as well, its been a big pull so give yourself a mental breather too. As such, it would be good if you can get yourself in the specific frame of mind before each session, to do that is probably just about spending 5-10min in silence before the session and making the mental commitment to be present with the session, so letting go of the events of the day. Ritual is powerful, you make a silent little commitment to anchor yourself in the session regardless of what happens in it. That practise is as important as the session itself because its teaching you how to set yourself for challenge, and that practise will follow you into race day and set your line for acceptance and presence when you need it most. Thats why we train, but think about what it is you need to train and where you lose your focus. Thats following you, its as important to deal with that as it is the physical aspects. Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - It is what it is #2
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o Don't bullshit yourself that a successful training session or race is anything other than a present moment. That's all there is to it. o Authenticity is the road to truth in an athletic process, people run out of steam because they create mental pictures that are impossible to live up to, why? Because it feels safer, it's rubbish, there is no safety. Get real and get after it. o Life is what you make of it, if you make it about drama, it will be drama, if you make it about fear it will be fear, if you make it about presence, your essential being will be present, nothing is more powerful than that. o Give up your ghosts, face the shadow that says you can't, take away the T an you have can, that's how close you really are.

Title: Program Notes-
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, . There is a play on ranges and intensities this week, pay attention and try not to cook it, it will be demanding enough by the end of the week. In each session try to think about where this the session applies to your racing, I do that when I program, surges in pace, climbs, short hills, flats etc, it all applies and the reason its important is because on race day you need to draw on the confidence that you have it covered in training, if we don't hold that awareness the knowledge is unconscious on race day and that can keep you stuck in a old paradigm on race day. So as we shift physically through these sessions we need to remind ourselves of where and how it applies. On race day when we need to take action, the knowledge helps us take action and importantly to be able to take a risk and move past the mental limitations that keep us bound to what we think we are capable of. Don't cook this, better to slightly under do it than even slightly overdo it at the moment, consistency is king. Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: AT/FTP Peppering -Repeat
WorkoutDescription: warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 1mint VO2 Trans 95-110rpm o 5mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling . Set 1 4x 5mins on 2mins rec at 90-102% of AT plus or minus 5bpm on 75-85rpm . Recovery -10mins easy rolling @ E1 . Repeat first set  Set 2 4x 5mins on 2mins rec at 90-102% of AT plus or minus 5bpm on 85-90rpm Finish the ride very aerobic to round out volume
CoachComments: Session is about really peppering your IAT workload for short periods of time on low rest periods, so we are working close to FTP on the button with little rest. It looks straight forward, it's a lot of work, you'll need good fuel post session. Also have a second look at cadence, there's an SE component hidden here, the best strength builder of all, SE, power and AT. Potent mix, needs fuel.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Association #3
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.
CoachComments: o Don't link your problems to thoughts, thoughts will always create a blame. o Leave your association to good and bad out of it, there is no good and bad, work with what is. o Don't defend your weakness's by associating them to the present moment. If you bring them up mentally in training, they will appear in your head when you least need them. o Thought is a lousy prosthetic to not feeling great, allow your experience to be what is, and work in the direction of acceptance.

Title: Program Notes: Power Phase one
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Ok, this has changed to power phase, Two speeds, on or off, no in between. Try to be a bit mindful of how you put this week together. Contrary to popular athletic opinion, true development does not come from outstanding sessions or killer weeks. Your resilience embeds itself among your conflicts, when you are tired, frustrated, angry, fatigued and fed up. When you are doubting yourself, and you dont know how to proceed, and you feel like you are down to fumes. When you are responding to shit you dont like in the same old way, and it dawns on you that you can do this differently this time. You can make a different choice here. This is your opportunity knocking. Let go of the story and give in, but do not give up! To be OK with not knowing about outcomes and just stay here. Have a great week,' Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Spike Power (ITU)
WorkoutDescription: Warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling. . Main Set: - 15x 1min effort (at or slightly above threshold, ie. 120-130% FTP; RPE best effort you can hold for 1min.). Efforts performed at race cadence 80-85rpm, 90secs easy spin recovery between efforts. Repeat this sequence 20 times or until cooked.. . Cool Down: - 10min easy/aerobic.
CoachComments: These are on the red line. But let it come, try not to force it, start the first 20secs building into the power then let it fly but keep in mind theres 8 of them.

CoachComments: This run is about fat burning low aerobic run form. Don't run so slow that the form is hampered but run where you are most comfortable on a cross benefit of form and function. Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - It is what it is #3
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o If you have a bad race or a bad session, what good does it do to ruminate? If it is, it's trying to teach you something, what is it trying to teach you? Listen to what is and you will find out. o Avoidance is the acid that eats at our dreams, its caustic, apathy takes a ride on it and creates frustration and then we think we are frustrated when in fact we are just avoidant. o Talk is good for movies, if you don't mean it and it's not really true, just don't say it, to yourself or to others. Actions speak louder than words. Action from where you are at right now, is best anchor to progress. o Progress is the sum of its parts. All of its parts arise from this place of what is, if it looks good, use it. If it looks bad, use it. Maximise what you have to work with.

Title: Fartlek Broken Swim
WorkoutDescription: warm up- 400m easy aerobic, 6x 50m e/h on 1:00 3000 main set - fartlek  5x100 on 20 rest E2B pull  break 30 secs  5x100 on 5 rest AT paddles only  break 30 secs  5x100 on 20 rest E2B pull  break 30 secs  5x100 on 5 rest AT paddles only  break 30 secs  5x100 on 20 rest E2B pull  break 30 secs  5x100 on 5 rest AT paddles only 500 mix with pull and extremely easy pace
CoachComments: Essentially this is five times 6x 100 broken but at fartlek speeds, the higher intensity efforts are low rest and the aerobic efforts are longer rest to give you the space to able to complete the higher intensity efforts with good form.

Title: Fast Track 400's
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 8x 400 AT+ on 400 walk/float recovery. . Warm down- 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: If this session cannot be done as track then do it as fartlek as- Warm up- 7mins E1 7mins E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 8x 90 seconds AT on 2:30 walk/float recovery. . Warm down - 7mins easy float. ...................... Run the 400 or 90secs on the threshold line or just below it. Don't blow your candles out by going overspeed. This is about the function of the whole session so we are looking for flow and function. Float the recovery by walking 200, then jog the next 200 keeping the heart rate at about 75-80% so its not totally off on the 200 float. We want your heart rate to come off but not totally off.

Title: Hour of Power
WorkoutDescription: Warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ E1 100rpm. . 60mins AT @ 105rpm. On the rivet. . Warm Down as - 10mins E1
CoachComments: threshold Buffering: So the 10min efforts are sitting below threshold =92-95% so it solid but it shouldn't be putting your lights out. Focus on the control of the power, the minds resistance. The recovery is not really a recovery, its E2B, roll the gear during that 5mins, we are looking for about 80-85% on about 70rpm. This is so the heart rate doesn't come all the way off but the cadence is low enough to lessen the drag on the oxygen system. Also be mindful of fuelling and this one will knock you about if you get fuel wrong.
AthleteComments: *19/09/2025 Aaron Kiss: mentally a pretty tough session. Had a bit of a lull in the middle 20mins but came back into it towards the end. Great session to do repeatedly and see the progression with the strength and nutrition tolerance*

Title: Speed focus Rating

CoachComments: Fartlek focus sets. Focus is to rate up on the speed sections without losing hold on the water, hense the recovery. There is 200 in between each set and thats there purely to reduce any lactate so very easy and take your time.
AthleteComments: *19/09/2025 Aaron Kiss: Great session, hopped in with kiwi triathlete joel lange so good to have some company on a speed set like this. 1:06s for the 100s, and built down from 0:32 to sub 30s for the 50s. Really tough but pushing the ceiling up and swimming really well at the moment*

Title: Track 200's
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 12x 200 @ threshold on 200 walk back recovery. . Warm down- 1200 E2A 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: TRACK VERSION: This session overspeed. But focus on turnover here. Start the effort building leg speed. Start the rep with feet shoulder width apart and lean from the ankles until you feel your toes claw the ground, this is correct lean angle, fall forward from that stance and let the leg speed come. Flow, relax and let it happen, by the end of the rep you want to be fast. The recovery is walk/jog, as slowly as you need to refract to the next rep. You can also do these as jog/walk back to start. NON TRACK VERSION: If you can't get to track all you need a 200 meter stretch of road or field. Walk/jog back to start. If that is the case the warm up becomes 8mins E1, 8mins E2A. Warm down 8mins E2A, 5mins E1.

Title: Open Water 70.3 Count/Rating Fartlek Focus
WorkoutDescription: Warm up- 10mins easy 5mins @ E2B low . Set 4x 5mins or 400meters on 90seconds stop recovery as - 30 strokes easy / 50 strokes 70.3 rating and pace. . Warmdown Easy 10-15mins.
CoachComments: The focus during the set is to count, Rate and Pace. When you are on the easy 30 strokes just go very easy and relaxed. Once you hit the 70.3 sections of 50-focus on rating up and swimming with focus and pace. There is a 90 seconds stop recovery, that is there to allow you to refocus and let the lactate come off. If you can't organise open water for this it will apply in the pool as the equiv of 400 meter reps

Title: Program Notes - Power
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, This one is packing bullets. Lets call it a breakthrough week at a week out. These weeks can be the catalyst for shift but only if its absorbed. That means you need to sleep well and eat properly and if there is stress is your life that you pay attention to when stress is high and lower the intensity. Stress is an anaerobic state, it creates a lack of oxygen and if you double down on intensity you are creating a oxygen debt in your body that can't be balanced. Thats the long way of saying don't push intensity when stress is present, back it down E2B. Work you way into these sessions, don't have them work you over.Ease in, no need to smash it at the start, invite your body to bring oxygen to each rep by keeping smooth and relaxed, as the intensity rises keep inviting the intensity to stay out of tension. Thats a practise and a very worthwhile one. You are now inviting oxygen, relaxation and down-regulation to be with intensity. It removes the judgment, the doubt and the fear around going into the hurt locker. Be the Christopher Columbus of your own relationship to pain, explore, be curious, run a self enquiry in each intensity session around what you can actually tolerate when under load. Whats the truth? What is pain? What is in my body and what resistance am I experiencing in my head? How do i give into what I don't want to feel? What happens when I soften into suffering? The above is having profound effects with the pro athletes i'm working with, It's available too all of us, not just pro athletes. It's just that pro athletes are more motivated than the rest of us to find hacks. Seriously this is the biggest hack I have ever stumbled on. Have a great week, Gilesy.

Title: Monas Classic Fartlek -Builder
WorkoutDescription: Warm up- 15mins easy 5mins build to E2B . Main set  o 3x 90seconds E3 low o 4x 60seconds E3-AT low o 4x 30seconds AT o 4x 15 seconds AT+ (Recovery time same as effort) . Warm Down= easy 15mins
CoachComments: This is the classic Monas Fartlek set. We start at 90secs effort on tempo, after three of those we drop to low AT on 4x 60secs, then 4x 30 at threshold, then 4x 15 at threshold plus. Looks short and uncomplex, has an amazing way of blowing your doors off, hence the reason Monas used it as a staple. Don't underestimate it and don't lose control of it. The rec time is same as effort (ie) 90 seconds effort/90seconds recovery float.

Title: Swim
WorkoutDescription: 400m swim 400m pull 400m fly swim 3x 10x 100m on 1:25pull boy/ 1:20/ 1:15 400m ezy

Title: Pace shifts AT four hundreds
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 300 easy 6x 50 building on 50, Main Set-(3x pull, 3xPull and paddles) 8x 400 on 5:30 - alternate- 30 strokes with force E3-AT but no tension 30 strokes relaxed E1 . Warm down- 300 pull 8x 50 on 55.
CoachComments: The main set is fartlek. Alternating force with easy relaxed swimming. When you move up from the relaxed pace try to apply force without tensing or creating mental tension. A good idea is to consciously try to relax as you apply the force. Often the tension is a physical reaction to a mental stimulus.

Title: AT Endurance Control Focus (Builder)
WorkoutDescription: Warmup pyramid as- o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling . AT Endurance Control Focus o 3x 4mins / AT low / rec 2min ezy 5mins ezy spin o 3x 3mins / AT sustained / rec 1 min 5mins ezy spin o 3x 2mins / Sprint =AT + 5 / 30secs rec . Warm down Easy gears to finish out ride volume.
CoachComments: This is an intense set. You'll need good control at the start. I want the cadence range at 80rpm please so yes it will be a big gear. Don't change the cadence at all, just use the gears to raise your intensity level. Feel into this one and have a look at the whole set before you start so you have a good sense of what is in front of you and that control will be key. Make your intensity change smooth, don't panic work on the feel and the form even in the AT+ range and work hard on not judging in your mind what is happening -let pain be there and accept everything you feel. Practice now so it comes out in races.

Title: Easy Aerobic Fat Burning
WorkoutDescription: Run- 60mins steady aerobic pace for time not km's on low E1. Preferably on dirt or on trail run, looking for some hills in the mix too.
CoachComments: The key here is to have a pace at the most relaxed effort that you possibly can. This is an easy aerobic run as we are putting back some quality low aerobic work so avoid going hard and take in the scenery.

Title: AT Threshold / E2B Low Recovery -
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 10mins E1 5mins build E2B low . Main Set - 4x 5mins / 5mins recovery, See pre-activity notes on this one. . Warm down 5mins E2B low 5mins jog 5mins walk
CoachComments: This set is equal effort and recovery. So its 5mins at low to mid AT then 5mins on low E2B pace, so its not back to easy, its back to mid aerobic pace. The idea is to learn how to recover and relax in the mid aerobic range after an effort. This promotes better general conditioning and better lactate buffering.

Title: Fartlek swim
WorkoutDescription: warm-up 800 easy 6x 50 on 55 rest fists drill . 10x 300 on 4:15- as  2x push entire effort E3  2x push 100 / float 100 / push 100  2x float 100 / push 100 / float 100  2x E2B paddles . warm down 800 mixed stroke
CoachComments: Fartlek pace variance session. Keep the gap between on and off far apart, literally super easy on the easy ones then really a focused push on the push sections. Pay close attention to your "tension" when you speed up, tension does not equate to speed. Swim fast, swim supple.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Non Resistance #3
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o All roads lead inwards, every outside hook is resistance dressed in sheep's clothing. When you catch yourself in outer resistance, go within and let it be the way it is. o All your challenges and discomforts are your opportunity's cloaked in the minds resistance, no one gets anywhere by attaching to feeling good and comfortable. Life teaches us most when we are stretched and out of our comfort zones. o The past is resistance, the future is resistance, don't look for safety in them, none exists. The only security you have is in this very moment, because that is all the reality we have. o Motivation is intrinsic, regardless of what you think motivates you, its coming from within, not without. If you think something motivates you, its not true, it simply uncovers your deeper truth, you already are motivation, it arises from within you. Thoughts and belief that is outside you is again, resistance.

Title: Program Notes
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Fuel well here, sleep well, dial it back if those two are out of sync. Bring a high degree of awareness to this week, it has the potential to bury you if you don't. Relax and feel your way into each effort, don't rush into efforts, let it come. The key focus is relaxation at speed. Thats a practicea deeply embodied focus. The more you relax, the more you can relax. The more you can relax, the more relaxed you become. Relaxation does not move upwards; it moves downwards. Its about calming yourself down within an intensity that wants to draw tension up. So when the screws are turning, dont turn yourself into a victim. Relax down into your feet. Breathe directly into the center of the intensity and discomfort. The more it hurts, the more you relax. Yes, you fucking can. You only think you cant because the tension is rising into your head. You gotta practise your way outta the tension habit. Consciously breathe the pain into your belly, into your feet. Bring that energy to the groundpractice again and againuntil the practice becomes automatic. Now, as you relax, you can relax. As you can relax, you do relax. And as you do relax, pain becomes an energetic movement, not a weight. It simply moves as you do. Relax into what you dont want to feel. Have a great week, Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Threshold Speed Developer -400 set Track
WorkoutDescription: Warm Up 10mins 5mins build to E2B . Main set  Interval with long recoveries 15 x 400 on around the 3min cycle or 2mins rec. 7x 95-105% of threshold 7x 100-110% of threshold . Warm Down- Easy 10mins
CoachComments: Build 7 @threshold and the build above. The focus is speed, turvover and lean angle. Oh, and relaxing....
AthleteComments: *01/10/2025 Aaron Kiss: Great session. Had some boys hop in for the same session but dropped the rest down to 60sec to sync up. Started out with 75s and dropped down to 66s for the last few. Feeling great and relaxed at speed*

Title: Speed focus Rating
WorkoutDescription: W/u- 3x 200 free / 50 backstroke 5 x 100 free descending each 25 . Set (speed)  10x 100 leave 1:45 fast  200 easy b/k  20 x 50 leave 60 secs fast  200 easy b/k  20x 25 leave 45 fast . 5x 100m backstroke
CoachComments: Fartlek focus sets. Focus is to rate up on the speed sections without losing hold on the water, hense the recovery. There is 200 in between each set and thats there purely to reduce any lactate so very easy and take your time.

Title: Spike Power (ITU)
WorkoutDescription: Warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling. . Main Set: - 15x 1min effort (at or slightly above threshold, ie. 120-130% FTP; RPE best effort you can hold for 1min.). Efforts performed at race cadence 80-85rpm, 90secs easy spin recovery between efforts. Repeat this sequence 20 times or until cooked.. . Cool Down: - 10min easy/aerobic.
CoachComments: These are on the red line. But let it come, try not to force it, start the first 20secs building into the power then let it fly but keep in mind theres 8 of them.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - It is what it is #2
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o Don't bullshit yourself that a successful training session or race is anything other than a present moment. That's all there is to it. o Authenticity is the road to truth in an athletic process, people run out of steam because they create mental pictures that are impossible to live up to, why? Because it feels safer, it's rubbish, there is no safety. Get real and get after it. o Life is what you make of it, if you make it about drama, it will be drama, if you make it about fear it will be fear, if you make it about presence, your essential being will be present, nothing is more powerful than that. o Give up your ghosts, face the shadow that says you can't, take away the T an you have can, that's how close you really are.

Title: Speed Endurance
WorkoutDescription: Warm up- 8x 50 first drill on 50 building Set 1- speed 3000 10x 100 fast but soft leaving on 30 rest 800 pull sub E1 5x 100 fast but soft leave 30 rest 300 pull sub E1 8x 50 fast on 60seconds rest . set 2 10x 100 30 rest very easy pull paddles . Warmdown Easy 200 mix.
CoachComments: These speed sets are set to fast, but relax as much as you can. Sounds like a paradox but it isn't, focus on your relaxation at speed.

Title: Speed Strength
WorkoutDescription: Warm Up- 5 x 100 free descending each 25 . Set 1 as- Speed Strength- (Pull and Paddles) o 600 E2B o 500 E3 o 400 AT o 300 AT o 200 AT o 100 AT+ o 4x 50 AT+ All on the 45 rest cycle. . Set 2 as- 10x 100 Pull / Paddles catch-up stroke on 20 rest -aerobic Warm down- 500 easy lope.
CoachComments: The main set hurts but it's a great strength builder. This was actually one of my own staples which I rarely program but I knew if I could swim this well I was in good form.

Title: Easy Aerobic Fat Burning
WorkoutDescription: Run- 60mins steady aerobic pace for time not km's on low E1. Preferably on dirt or on trail run, looking for some hills in the mix too.
CoachComments: The key here is to have a pace at the most relaxed effort that you possibly can. This is an easy aerobic run as we are putting back some quality low aerobic work so avoid going hard and take in the scenery.

Title: Track 200's
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 12x 200 @ threshold on 200 walk back recovery. . Warm down- 1200 E2A 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: TRACK VERSION: This session overspeed. But focus on turnover here. Start the effort building leg speed. Start the rep with feet shoulder width apart and lean from the ankles until you feel your toes claw the ground, this is correct lean angle, fall forward from that stance and let the leg speed come. Flow, relax and let it happen, by the end of the rep you want to be fast. The recovery is walk/jog, as slowly as you need to refract to the next rep. You can also do these as jog/walk back to start. NON TRACK VERSION: If you can't get to track all you need a 200 meter stretch of road or field. Walk/jog back to start. If that is the case the warm up becomes 8mins E1, 8mins E2A. Warm down 8mins E2A, 5mins E1.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Limited/Unlimited # 1
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.

Title: Hour of Power
WorkoutDescription: Warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ E1 100rpm. . 60mins AT @ 105rpm. On the rivet. . ROTB
CoachComments: threshold Buffering: So the 10min efforts are sitting below threshold =92-95% so it solid but it shouldn't be putting your lights out. Focus on the control of the power, the minds resistance. The recovery is not really a recovery, its E2B, roll the gear during that 5mins, we are looking for about 80-85% on about 70rpm. This is so the heart rate doesn't come all the way off but the cadence is low enough to lessen the drag on the oxygen system. Also be mindful of fuelling and this one will knock you about if you get fuel wrong.
AthleteComments: *04/10/2025 Aaron Kiss: 299NP for the effort best one yet. That was tough*

Title: Open Water Beach start 200s

CoachComments: The focus here is start. Try to start and have less breaths at the start (ie) stroking 4-5 times without breath, remember though not to hold breath - breathe it out over the entire time your head is in the water.

Title: Short Speed Reps
WorkoutDescription: Warm up- 400 free every 4th 50 bk 8x 50 first drill on 50 building . Set- speed 1800 16x 25 @ high speed leave on 45 seconds 200 float easy 8x 50 @ speed leave on 2mins 200 float easy 4x 100 @ speed leave on 2:30 200 float easy . 8x 50 pull sub E1 on 15 rest.
CoachComments: The focus here for main set is speed. We are looking for high rating through the 25/50 sets but relax at the same time. Focus on pulling your body across your arms and apply the force through your lats not your shoulders.

Title: Program Notes
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Lets get you on the start line fresh mate. Key sessions spread in a different week structure aimed at absorption of the suck and backdown for the race. Keep the aerobic sessions really aerobic, but hold form. If you are feeling it on Monday, lose the rec swim and rest it out to be back on deck for Tuesday. The real path to excellence demands something harder than endless training  it requires trust. Trust in your body's signals. Trust in the recovery process. Trust that less can deliver more. Consider digestion as a metaphor. Your body can only process one meal at a time. Force-feeding yourself five meals at once doesn't make you five times stronger  it makes you sick. Training works the same way. When you pile on excessive workouts without proper recovery, you're not building strength; you're creating debt your body can't repay. The solution isn't complicated, but it challenges everything you've been taught about success. Stop fighting your body's wisdom. Start treating discomfort as information rather than an enemy to overcome. Your fatigue, soreness, and energy fluctuations aren't weaknesses  they're your body's intelligence speaking to you. This approach requires courage. It takes more bravery to rest when everyone else is training than to push through another exhausting session. But this is how champions emerge. They don't just train differently; they think differently. Have a great week, Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Low hrate run - Strides
WorkoutDescription: A 60min dead flat run. Run at the lowest possible oxygen cost for the best form. Incorporate 5x 60seconds building to high turnover on the 3min cycle.
CoachComments: This run is about fat burning low aerobic run form. Don't run so slow that the form is hampered but run where you are most comfortable on a cross benefit of form and function

Title: Low AT / E2B / One to one ratio -Builder new
WorkoutDescription: Warmup pyramid as- o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling . Low AT / E2B / One to one ratio> 5x 5mins / 5mins low E2B in recovery, cadence 80-85rpm, . Warm down- 10mins easy tapping.
CoachComments: This is a one to one ratio. So 5mins low AT, no higher than 90-92% of FTP. The recovery between the efforts is low E2B, this gives better lactate clearance and brings better flow to the session, so you are not backing all the way off or out.

Title: Swim
WorkoutDescription: 400m swim 400m pull 400m fly swim 3x 10x 100m on 1:25pull boy/ 1:20/ 1:15 400m ezy

Title: Aerobic Form Climbs Road
WorkoutDescription: Aerobic endurance on climbs. Keep all climbs seated and E2B or level. Keep the flats light around E1-E2A.
CoachComments: Use gravity here, ride the climbs slow, pedalling smoothly and keeping your upper body relaxed. As the inertia is low the strength benefit is maximised giving you a good workout of strength benefit for low aerobic cost. Leave the ego on the shelf and check your form, are you unnecessarily moving the body to add to momentum? Isolate the working muscles and remind yourself to breathe and relax into it.

Title: Pace shifts AT four hundreds
WorkoutDescription: Warm up 300 easy 6x 50 building on 15 rest, Main Set-(3x pull, 2xPull and paddles) 5x 400 on 40 rest as - alternate- 30 strokes with force E3-AT but no tension 30 strokes relaxed E1 . Warm down- 300 pull 4x 50 on 20 rest.
CoachComments: The main set is fartlek. Alternating force with easy relaxed swimming. When you move up from the relaxed pace try to apply force without tensing or creating mental tension. A good idea is to consciously try to relax as you apply the force. Often the tension is a physical reaction to a mental stimulus.

Title: Notes-Race Week Asia Triathlon Cup
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Lets not reinvent the wheel mate, so keep everything as close to normal this week as possible including this taper. We want you on the line fresh and healthy. So its the same taper to eliminate any doubts. Keep it simple, do your grounding, stay with yourself. Breathe, relax the tension in the front of your body constantly and consistently. Keep this super simple and enough here to keep you moving. Do the vis, keep yourself calm, breathe into your balls often this week and prepare to go deep. Don't change anything. Don't go looking for more. Let the racing do the work. Avoid touching it up in training. Don't test, trust! Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Program Notes:
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, A targeted Week coming out of the race, volume a little more aerobic work. Comfortably uncomfortable, you should be able to relax in this zone and be very solid at the same time, thats the focus. fuel well and sleep well here. Be mindful that its not a drain, its a pain! Those two are not the same thing. Its the mind that makes an association with "being" drained. If you stay fully present in the process as it unfolds, its far less weight physically and mentally. So yes, theres a physical cost no doubt, but be kind to yourself by not adding to it with heavy resistant thought, and the key to it is simply to stay where you are. Let the thoughts come but don't entertain them, and, as they rise into your head, you keep dropping your focus back to your body, this is the meaning of the term embodiment. The simple metaphor is, be in your feet. Have a great week, Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Aerobic threshold, Low rec resets-
WorkoutDescription: Warm up- o 5mins walk o10mins E1 o 5mins E2A high . Aerobic Threshold low rec reset- 9x 5mins on 45 second walk reset . Warm down- o 5mins E2B low o 10mins E1 float easy o 5mins walk
CoachComments: The idea here is Aerobic threshold pace with a 45 second reset after every 5mins, why? Because of a few reasons-the 45seconds lets the heart rate come down and allows better aerobic speed through that 5mins because of it. The 45 seconds perhaps more importantly allows a form reset, use that space to check your lean angle to make sure you are leaning from the ankles slightly forwards to reset your relaxed focus. So the ultimate benefit here is for your overall efficiency and many people miss this opportunity seeing the rest as unnecessary but think of it this way, the habits in these efforts are the habits you will automatically carry into races, i prefer to create enough space that these efforts carry ultimate quality not junky uneven effort that will carry the same way into races.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Flow #2- Reminders
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.
CoachComments: o No flow, no go. Disjointed performances are a by-product of a lack of flow. In flow- it goes fast, out of flow its like pulling teeth. o Use mental cues to gently bring yourself back to flow and process. o Pour the focus of the performance through the self, always through the self. This is your definition of self-trust. o The powered focus of desire, gut and heart, it comes from the center, not the mind.

Title: Low Cad -Power SE

CoachComments: Power SE Harder than it looks, the recovery refractory is not all the way off and the efforts themselves are heavy SE power. Pay attention to each rep and don't get ahead of yourself. Also be mindful of fuelling and this one will knock you about if you get fuel wrong.

Title: Tempo Endurance 400 set Track
WorkoutDescription: Warm Up 10mins 5mins build to E2B . Main set  Interval with short recoveries 15 x 400 or 90 seconds at 10-15km race pace leaving on 45secs rest off each effort . Warm Down- Easy 10mins
CoachComments: So these are done at tempo E3 so it's solid but it is sustainable. The goal of the session is to reach the final 400's with strongest form so starting conservative is important.

Title: Speed Strength
WorkoutDescription: Warm Up- 800 easy 5x 100 free descending each 25 on 1:45 . Set 1 as- Speed Strength- (Pull and Paddles) o 600 E2B o 500 E3 o 400 AT o 300 AT o 200 AT o 100 AT+ o 4x 50 AT+ All on the 1:30 cycle. . Warm down- 500 easy lope. 8x 50 easy pull on 60secs

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Sensing #1
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.
CoachComments: o How much can you sense at once? Use pure awareness to find out. Don't think, sense. o What happens when pain is present without thought? Force it to be felt, not thought. o Go directly to the center of your pain and hang out there, stay in the center, don't allow it to become a thought. o Don't allow pain to rise into your head, keep it where you are meant to feel it.

Title: Aerobic Form Climbs Road
WorkoutDescription: Aerobic endurance on climbs. Keep all climbs seated and E2B or level. Keep the flats light around E1-E2A.
CoachComments: Use gravity here, ride the climbs slow, pedalling smoothly and keeping your upper body relaxed. As the inertia is low the strength benefit is maximised giving you a good workout of strength benefit for low aerobic cost. Leave the ego on the shelf and check your form, are you unnecessarily moving the body to add to momentum? Isolate the working muscles and remind yourself to breathe and relax into it.

Title: ROTB
WorkoutDescription: ROTB as- . 3x 5mins tempo E2B IMP relaxed and strong on 5mins easy in between. 10mins easy E1.

Title: Endurance low aerobic before run

Title: Back End E2B Run-
WorkoutDescription: Warm up Walk 10mins run 30mins easy E1-E2A 5mins build to E2B . Set (Back end Aerobic Function) 30mins @ IMP speed=E2B low to mid . Warm down- 5mins E2A 5mins E1 10mins walking.
CoachComments: This set is all about aerobic function. I want you to run best possible form and speed for an aerobic threshold cost over the back-end of this run. Focus on your turnover and relaxing into it as you build in the IMP section. Take water so you can stay hydrated.

Title: Open Water Beach start 200s

CoachComments: The focus here is start. Try to start and have less breaths at the start (ie) stroking 4-5 times without breath, remember though not to hold breath - breathe it out over the entire time your head is in the water.

Title: Recovery Session

Title: Program Notes:
WorkoutDescription: Hi Aaron, Program dominated by key leg days and stand alone swims. Build run is back in there for Sunday so focus hard on pacing there and don't cook it early. Try to be a bit mindful of how you put this week together. Contrary to popular athletic opinion, true development does not come from outstanding sessions or killer weeks. Your resilience embeds itself among your conflicts, when you are tired, frustrated, angry, fatigued and fed up. When you are doubting yourself, and you dont know how to proceed, and you feel like you are down to fumes. When you are responding to shit you dont like in the same old way, and it dawns on you that you can do this differently this time. You can make a different choice here. This is your opportunity knocking. Let go of the story and give in, but do not give up! To be OK with not knowing about outcomes and just stay here. Have a great week,' Cheers, Gilesy.

Title: Threshold Buffering
WorkoutDescription: Warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ E1 100rpm. . Threshold Buffer: 3x 10mins @ Threshold Power = 80-85rpm / 5mins @ E2B on 70-75rpm. . Warm Down as - 10mins E1
CoachComments: threshold Buffering: So the 10min efforts are sitting below threshold =92-95% so it solid but it shouldn't be putting your lights out. Focus on the control of the power, the minds resistance. The recovery is not really a recovery, its E2B, roll the gear during that 5mins, we are looking for about 80-85% on about 70rpm. This is so the heart rate doesn't come all the way off but the cadence is low enough to lessen the drag on the oxygen system. Also be mindful of fuelling and this one will knock you about if you get fuel wrong.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - It is what it is #3
WorkoutDescription: Pre session prep 5 mins contemplate and relaxed breathing. o If you have a bad race or a bad session, what good does it do to ruminate? If it is, it's trying to teach you something, what is it trying to teach you? Listen to what is and you will find out. o Avoidance is the acid that eats at our dreams, its caustic, apathy takes a ride on it and creates frustration and then we think we are frustrated when in fact we are just avoidant. o Talk is good for movies, if you don't mean it and it's not really true, just don't say it, to yourself or to others. Actions speak louder than words. Action from where you are at right now, is best anchor to progress. o Progress is the sum of its parts. All of its parts arise from this place of what is, if it looks good, use it. If it looks bad, use it. Maximise what you have to work with.

Title: Endurance low aerobic
WorkoutDescription: Low aerobic 60mins @ sub E1. Pedaling at all times but at light intensity to preserve power and keep legs supple.

Title: Track 1500's
WorkoutDescription: Warmup as- 1600 Meters E1 1600 Meters E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 4x 1500 low to mid AT on 400 walk/float recovery. . Warm down- 1000 easy float.
CoachComments: If this session cannot be done as track then do it as fartlek as- Warm up- 7mins E1 7mins E2A-E2B low . Main Set- 5x 5:30mins mid AT on 2:30 walk/float recovery. . Warm down - 7mins easy float. ...................... Run the 1500 or 5:30mins on the low to mid threshold range. Don't blow your candles out by going overspeed. This is about the function of the whole session so we are looking for flow and function. Float the recovery by walking 200, then jog the next 200 keeping the heart rate at about 75-80% so its not totally off on the 200 float. We want your heart rate to come off but not totally off. Be careful not to overdo the first 500, let it build.

Title: Endurance low aerobic
WorkoutDescription: Low aerobic 2.5hours @ sub E1. Pedaling at all times but at light intensity to preserve power and keep legs supple.

Title: Low hrate run
WorkoutDescription: A 90min dead flat run. Run at the lowest possible oxygen cost for the best form.
CoachComments: This run is about fat burning low aerobic run form. Don't run so slow that the form is hampered but run where you are most comfortable on a cross benefit of form and function. To Avoid overreaching and overtraining it's best to keep these aerobic sessions very aerobic (ie) easy. You can still create and overload of neuromuscular damage by training in the grey area. There's no need to ride these even remotely solid so nice and even and very easy is safest option.

Title: Speed Strength
WorkoutDescription: Warm Up- 5 x 100 free descending each 25 . Set 1 as- Speed Strength- (Pull and Paddles) o 600 E2B o 500 E3 o 400 AT o 300 AT o 200 AT o 100 AT+ o 4x 50 AT+ All on the 45 rest cycle. . Set 2 as- 10x 100 Pull / Paddles catch-up stroke on 20 rest -aerobic Warm down- 500 easy lope.

Title: Endurance IMP
WorkoutDescription: warm up 10mins easy 5mins E2A . IMP Set 2- 2x 20mins @ IMP on 7mins recovery. Cadence in the sweet spot 80-85rpm or where it feels best for you. . 30mins E1
CoachComments: Ironman pace reps, prefer flat to rolling course, focus pressure through the pedal stroke smoothly to move into the IMP zone -make that shift as an application of power not an application of mental effort. Its important to embody this feeling, hence the longer reps, get inside it, what does it feel like, how can i get to know this feeling well enough for it to feel instinctual? Thats where you want the focus of this session to go.

Title: Speed Endurance

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - Move towards pain
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.

Become the conduit to pain. o If pain is arising in the body, feel it fully, do not disassociate o Moving away from tagging conditions. Drop the tags, drop the labels, it as it is. .

Title: Fartlek Broken Swim
WorkoutDescription: warm up- 400m easy aerobic, 6x 50m e/h on 1:00 3000 main set - fartlek  5x100 on 20 rest E2B pull  break 30 secs  5x100 on 5 rest AT paddles only  break 30 secs  5x100 on 20 rest E2B pull  break 30 secs  5x100 on 5 rest AT paddles only  break 30 secs  5x100 on 20 rest E2B pull  break 30 secs  5x100 on 5 rest AT paddles only 500 mix with pull and extremely easy pace
CoachComments: Essentially this is five times 6x 100 broken but at fartlek speeds, the higher intensity efforts are low rest and the aerobic efforts are longer rest to give you the space to able to complete the higher intensity efforts with good form.

Title: Threshold Building Session (8 x 3min efforts)
WorkoutDescription: Warm up o 5mins @ E1 85rpm, o 5mins @ E2a 90rpm, o 3mins @ E2b 95rpm o 1mins @ E3 100rpm o 3mins @ RC- E1 70- 80rpm easy rolling. . Main Set: - 8x 3min effort (at or slightly above threshold, ie. 100-110% FTP; RPE best effort you can hold for 3min.). Efforts performed at race cadence 80-85rpm, 2min easy spin recovery between efforts. Repeat this sequence 8 times. . Cool Down: - 10min easy/aerobic.
CoachComments: These are on the red line. But let it come, try not to force it, start the first 20secs building into the power then let it fly but keep in mind theres 8 of them.

Title: ROTB Fast
WorkoutDescription: Run off the bike. 2km's @ fast. Sub 3:15 if possible. Walk warm down - 10mins.

Title: Psych Tip for sessions today - NOW #1
WorkoutDescription: Before the start of the sessions today take 5 mins to center yourself. Take the time to sit and contemplate the following four statements, align yourself with them and focus on them completely brining yourself into presence with the sessions and allowing the events of the day to dissolve.
